content.problemStatement:
- When you set a **width** and **height** for an element in CSS, by default it only applies to the **content** of the element. 
- Any **padding** or **border** you add will **increase the total size** of the element.This can make layout calculations tricky.
---
**Example (default `box-sizing: content-box`)**

```css
.box {
  width: 200px;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 5px solid blue;
}
```

* **Content width**: 200px
* **Padding**: 20px on each side → adds 40px
* **Border**: 5px on each side → adds 10px
* **Total width**: 200 + 40 + 10 = 250px

Notice that the **actual rendered box is wider than the width you set**.

---
**Solution: `box-sizing: border-box`**

By using `box-sizing: border-box`, the **width and height include padding and border**. This makes **layout easier to manage**, because the total size will be exactly what you set.

```css
.box {
  width: 200px;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 5px solid blue;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```
* **Total width** = 200px (padding and border are included inside this)
* Now your layout will stay **consistent**, even if you add padding or borders.

**It will be more clear in the next page(Worked Example).**

